@flexiarg t3/transformation-space
@title Transformation Space
@sigils [🏗️/场]
@audience implementation-researchers, programme-architects, funders
@tone formal-analytic
@style design-pattern
@part Open Research Training
@see t3/intervention-triad, t3/architectural-pair, t3/capability-not-functioning
@next t3/intervention-triad
@length 180-260
@allow-new-claims false

! conclusion:
  Open research training operates within a transformation space — a set of institutional structures, incentive systems, workload models, and feedback mechanisms — that determines its outcomes regardless of input quality. The programme's primary constraint is not the quality of its training inputs but the institutional architecture through which those inputs are — or are not — translated into routine practice.

  + context: A persistent practice gap separates attending open research training from routinely working differently; this is compounded by a research gap — the literature evaluates training content and satisfaction but not the implementation processes through which training does or does not translate into sustained practice change. Because we have not studied implementation, we lack the concepts and evidence needed to diagnose why the practice gap persists.
  + if: You want to understand why well-designed training does not reliably produce practice change, and why studying training inputs alone cannot answer that question.
  + however: Most programme evaluation focuses on improving the training input (content, pedagogy, materials) without examining the institutional architecture that receives it; train-the-trainer models add further implementation challenges — translation, institutional support, workload, materials maintenance — each a potential point of failure.
  + then: Analyse the transformation space: the institutional structures, incentive systems, workload models, and feedback mechanisms that determine whether any training input — however well-designed — produces lasting collective change. Use NPT to map social processes and COM-B to diagnose individual-level bottlenecks.
  + because: Improving the input is necessary but not sufficient; without architectural capacity to receive, amplify, and sustain what training produces, impact depends on individual goodwill and decays when that goodwill is exhausted.
      + mechanism: Institutional architecture multiplies or absorbs training inputs depending on the presence of receiving structures (workload allocation, feedback systems, co-ownership pathways).
      + counterfactual: If we only improve training design without addressing architecture, we produce better-trained individuals in unchanged institutions, and normalisation fails.
      + applies-when: A programme operates across multiple institutions with heterogeneous infrastructure and no direct control over local conditions.
      + does-not-apply: A single-site pilot with full institutional backing and dedicated resources.
      + signals: Motivated, capable trainers report inability to sustain delivery; the same training produces divergent outcomes across institutions.
      + evidence: T3 immediate survey — motivation items M>5.3, institutional measurement items M<3.4; qualitative implementation modes show architecture, not motivation, as differentiator.
  + next-steps:
      - Distinguish intervention-level from architecture-level findings in programme evaluation.
      - Map institutional receiving structures before designing training inputs.
      - Design evaluation frameworks that assess architectural capacity alongside training quality.
  + governance:
      - practice: include architectural assessment in programme evaluation cycles.
      - metric: proportion of institutions with identifiable receiving structures for training outputs.
